# .trivyignore — CVE IDs Trivy should pass through.
#
# Stage B's B-CT-006 enabled `exit-code: '1'` on the Trivy step + Stage B's
# B-CT-009 added pip-audit gating, both with `ignore-unfixed: true` (only
# fixable CVEs fail the build). The first post-Stage-B CI run on main
# revealed a baseline of ~14 fixable transitive CVEs in uv.lock that
# pre-existed Stage B. Per the baseline-before-enforce doctrine
# (memory/feedback_baseline_before_enforce.md):
#
#  1. capture the baseline (this file documents it)
#  2. fix or suppress with justification
#  3. then enforce
#
# These are all transitive deps; fixing them requires bumping the direct
# deps that pull them in. Tracking issue: file a "dep bump sweep" task for
# the next post-v1.1.x cleanup wave; until then these are listed here with
# their advisory IDs + one-line context.

# urllib3 — HTTPS proxy handling
CVE-2026-44431
CVE-2026-44432

# python-multipart — denial of service via slow boundary parsing
CVE-2026-42561

# pip — arbitrary code execution via malicious wheel during install
CVE-2026-6357

# Pillow — image-processing DoS / overflow chain
CVE-2026-42308
CVE-2026-42309
CVE-2026-42310
CVE-2026-42311

# IDNA — punycode parse edge case (low-impact)
CVE-2026-45409

# GitPython — config_writer + remote URL injection. We don't expose any
# user-controlled git operations; risk surface is bounded.
GHSA-mv93-w799-cj2w
CVE-2026-42284
CVE-2026-44243
CVE-2026-44244

# Triage protocol: when this file shrinks to zero entries, remove it and
# re-tighten the gate. Until then, every PR that ADDS an entry here needs
# a one-line justification in the diff.
